-- Cairn India CEO Dhir Gets $10.5 Million Selling Half His Shares
-- B y   R a k t e e m   K a t a k e y
-- 2012-02-02T05:03:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-02/cairn-india-ceo-dhir-gets-10-5-million-selling-half-his-shares.html
Rahul Dhir, the chief executive
officer of  Cairn India Ltd. (CAIR) , sold more than half of his
shareholding for 512.7 million rupees ($10.5 million).  Dhir sold 1.5 million shares in five transactions from Jan.
30 to Feb. 1 through the  stock exchanges , according to a
regulatory filing today. He now holds 1.3 million shares,
according to the filing.  The CEO couldnâ€™t immediately be reached for comment on his
mobile phone, which was switched off.  The sale by Dhir was the first since the energy explorer
was acquired by  Vedanta Resources Plc (VED)  last year. Dhir previously
sold shares in Cairn India in 2009.  He offloaded 1.5 million  shares  on Aug. 5, 2009, at 240.05
rupees each and 196,139 shares at 242.45 rupees apiece the next
day, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. He bought 1.6
million shares at 142.85 rupees each on Dec. 8, 2008, and
638,078 shares at 152.95 rupees each on Dec. 19 that year,
according to the data.  Cairn  India  fell 1.9 percent to 340.25 rupees at 9:32 a.m.
in Mumbai. The stock  rose  8 percent in January, the fourth month
of gains.  Vedanta Resources, a London-listed mining company with no
experience in oil and gas production, and its unit  hold  59
percent in Cairn India after completing the acquisition in
December. Dhir received a salary and bonus of 68.8 million
rupees in the year ended March 2011, according to data compiled
by Bloomberg.  To contact the reporter on this story:
